# Command valkey-cli

## What does this command do:

Command line interface for Valkey key-value databases, optimized for caching and other realtime workloads. Compatible with Redis protocol.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: sudo dnf install valkey
For Raspberry Pi install using: sudo apt install valkey
For Mac install using: brew install valkey

## Command path

For Fedora run: valkey-cli
For Raspberry Pi run: valkey-cli
For Mac run: valkey-cli

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://valkey.io/topics/installation/

## Command options

# Start interactive REPL (connects to 127.0.0.1:6379 by default):
valkey-cli

# Connect to a specific host and port:
valkey-cli -h <host> -p <port>

# Authenticate with password (prefer REDISCLI_AUTH env var):
valkey-cli -a <password>
REDISCLI_AUTH=<password> valkey-cli

# Connect via URI:
valkey-cli -u valkey://user:pass@host:port/db

# Select database number:
valkey-cli -n <db>

# Test connectivity (returns PONG):
valkey-cli ping

# Set a key:
valkey-cli set <key> <value>

# Get a key's value:
valkey-cli get <key>

# Delete a key:
valkey-cli del <key>

# List keys matching pattern (avoid on large datasets — blocks server):
valkey-cli keys <pattern>

# Safely iterate keys without blocking (use in production):
valkey-cli --scan --pattern '<pattern>'
valkey-cli --scan --pattern '<pattern>' --count 100

# Show server info and stats:
valkey-cli info

# Rolling real-time server stats (mem, clients, etc.):
valkey-cli --stat

# Continuously sample server latency:
valkey-cli --latency

# Find keys with the most elements:
valkey-cli --bigkeys

# Find keys consuming the most memory:
valkey-cli --memkeys

# Find frequently accessed keys (requires LFU maxmemory-policy):
valkey-cli --hotkeys

# Dump remote RDB snapshot to local file:
valkey-cli --rdb <filename>

# Send raw RESP protocol from stdin (bulk import):
valkey-cli --pipe

# Repeat a command N times:
valkey-cli -r <n> <cmd>

# Repeat with interval (seconds) between executions:
valkey-cli -r <n> -i <interval> <cmd>

# Output results in CSV format:
valkey-cli --csv <cmd>

# Output results in JSON format (RESP3):
valkey-cli --json <cmd>

# Enable cluster mode (follow MOVED/ASK redirections):
valkey-cli -c -h <host> -p <port>

# List all cluster management subcommands:
valkey-cli --cluster help

# Connect with TLS:
valkey-cli --tls --cert <cert-file> --key <key-file> --cacert <ca-file>

# Run a Lua script via EVAL (comma separates KEYS from ARGV):
valkey-cli --eval <script.lua> key1 key2 , arg1 arg2

# Read last argument from STDIN:
cat /etc/passwd | valkey-cli -x set mypasswd

# Connection flags summary:
# -h <host>       server hostname (default: 127.0.0.1)
# -p <port>       server port (default: 6379)
# -s <socket>     unix socket (overrides host/port)
# -n <db>         database number
# -a <password>   password
# -u <uri>        valkey://user:pass@host:port/db
# --user <name>   ACL username (use with -a)
# -c              cluster mode
# -4 / -6         prefer IPv4 / IPv6

# Output flags summary:
# --raw           raw output (default when stdout is not a tty)
# --no-raw        force formatted output
# --csv           CSV format
# --json          JSON format (RESP3)
# --quoted-json   ASCII-safe quoted JSON
